<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-02-09T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-02-09T02:00:00-05:00" n="65" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d65">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/2–948: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Vice Consul at Mukden</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">McKelvey</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Mukden</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-02-09T15:00:00+08:00">February
                                    9, 1948—3 p. m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received February 9—9:05 a. m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>71. Communists capture Liaoyang (mytel 66 to Department February 5<note n="37" xml:id="d65fn37">Not printed.</note>) confirmed. Government
                            losses inside Liaoyang not known-One Government division attempting
                            break siege, flanked by Communists and reported two of three Government
                            regiments lost.</p>
                        <p>Sent Embassy as 105; repeated Department as 71, Tientsin 54, Peiping
                            58.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">McKelvey</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>